    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3485033257" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3485033257" />
    <a title="Jonathan Pool" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27950748-jonathan-pool"><img alt="Jonathan Pool" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1484567350p2/27950748.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3485033257?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan Pool" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan Pool" href="/user/show/27950748-jonathan-pool">Jonathan Pool</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27950748-jonathan-pool?shelf=international">international</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3485033257" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3091790886175367093"><u>Themes</u> <br/><br/>Dangarembga has multiple targets, sometimes over lapping.<br/><br/>* Colonialism. The enduring curse that besets a nation. The title Nervous Conditions is taken from Jean-Paul Sartre&apos;s introduction to Franz Fanon&apos;s <b> The Wretched of the Earth</b>. The &quot;nervous condition&quot; of the native is, according to Sartre, a function of mutually reinforcing attitudes between coloniser and colonised that condemn the colonised to what amounts to a psychological disorder.    <br/>Fanon himself was a psychiatrist.<br/>This is the </span>
  <span id="freeText3091790886175367093" style="display:none"><u>Themes</u> <br /><br />Dangarembga has multiple targets, sometimes over lapping.<br /><br />* Colonialism. The enduring curse that besets a nation. The title Nervous Conditions is taken from Jean-Paul Sartre's introduction to Franz Fanon's <b> The Wretched of the Earth</b>. The "nervous condition" of the native is, according to Sartre, a function of mutually reinforcing attitudes between coloniser and colonised that condemn the colonised to what amounts to a psychological disorder.    <br />Fanon himself was a psychiatrist.<br />This is the dominant (but not exclusive) theme of Dangarembga’s trilogy of novels, applied to her native Rhodesia/ Zimbabwe.<br /><br />* Suppression of women. And it starts at a young age. Tambu’s brother, Nhamo, is advised by his boy mates, aged about thirteen:“<i> Why talk? Just hit. That’s what they hear”</i>(23) <br /><br />* The Patriarchal Society. Nyasha’s perspective about her father: ”it’s not really him you know. It’s everything, it’s everywhere. So where do you break out to? You’re just one person and it’s everywhere.”(174)<br /><br />* Education. Mission Schools, and Catholic nuns (Young Ladies College of The Sacred Heart). A way to progress from harvesting the fields for “Mealies”.<br /> <br /><u>Synopsis</u> <br /> <br />Its not that often that a novel’s primary character, and its narrating voice, is for the most part entirely unlikeable.  That’s the case with Tambu(dzai) Sigauke. Tambu has an inflated sense of her own self importance, and she labours under the misapprehension that she is destined for great things.  Being lucky enough to benefit from a formal education, Tambu mistakenly thinks that academic success will pave the way for her to achieve status in employment and the esteem of those around her. <br />Set near Umtali (third largest city in Rhodesia), Tambu (born 1955) sets out the message of the book from the outset: <i> “ My story is about my escape and Lucia’s; about my mothers and Maiguru’s entrapment; and about Nyasha’s rebellion“ </i> (1).  Five women constrained by Rhodesia’s patriarchal family structure, and who are beholden to Tambu’s weak and lazy father, Jeremiah; and in particular his brother (Tambu’s Uncle) and effective family head, Babamukuru. <br />Tambu is withering about her father <i> “His usual ability to jump whichever way was easiest “</i> <br />His guidance for his daughters <i>  “Learn to cook and clean. Grow vegetables “</i>15) <br />Babamukuru (A young girl calls her father's older brother babamukuru (literally, older father = uncle), is headmaster of the (missionary founded) selective primary school. He is a rigidly unyielding bully.  <br />It was <i> “necessary to efface yourself in order to preserve his (Baba) sense of identity and value”</i> (102).  <br />and,  <br /><i>“Anyone who defies my authority is an evil thing in this house”</i>(167) <br /> <br />Babamukuru is especially hard on his own daughter, Nyasha, <i>“All these conflicts came back to this question of femaleness. Femaleness as opposed and inferior to maleness”</i> (116) <br /> <br /> <br /><u>Historical context</u> <br /><br /> The book is set in the early 1960’s, a time when the eyes of the world were on Ian Smith; his Unilateral Declaration of Independence and the consequent escalation of unrest and demands for freedom from White Rule that was sweeping through Africa.<br />Dangarembga is cleverly obscure in her implications about racial <br />The most clear cut example is when<br />Nyasha gets severe anorexia. She blames “them” : a hundred years of making everybody trapped (their history).<br /> <br /> <br /><u>Author background &amp; Reviews</u> <br /> <br />Dangarembga  was only twenty five when Nervous Conditions was published in 1988 was awarded the Commonwealth Writer’s Prize in 1989; it was named by the BBC in 2018 as no. 66 in the top 100 books that have shaped the world, and it is widely recognised as a major literary contribution to African feminism and postcolonial literature.  It’s the first part of a trilogy, and the most recent part, published in 2018 <b> This Mournable Body” </b> is the book I expect to win the Booker Prize in 2020 <br /> <br /><u>Recommend </u> <br /><br />Tsitsi Dangarembga has an unmistakeable writing style. Laced with sardonic comment, sarcasm and withering vitriol.  The underlying messages are subtlely introduced and re-enforced. It’s a good book that poses as many questions as answers.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3091790886175367093" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


