    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_220311797" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/220311797" />
    <a title="Mikki" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2757888-mikki"><img alt="Mikki" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1376784536p2/2757888.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/220311797?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mikki" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mikki" href="/user/show/2757888-mikki">Mikki</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2757888-mikki?shelf=africa">africa</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer220311797" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer384721922019066626">What I loved most about this book was the underlying story of coming to self and not so much to age. In first person narrative, Tambu, a 14 year old Zimbabwean, speaks directly to the reader telling not only her story of growing up female in a patriarchal society, but also those of the women around her. <br/><br/>In the opening sentence, Tambu makes no apologies regarding her lack of emotion toward her brother&apos;s death. Because with no other male children in the family, she is now the one afforded the oppo</span>
  <span id="freeText384721922019066626" style="display:none">What I loved most about this book was the underlying story of coming to self and not so much to age. In first person narrative, Tambu, a 14 year old Zimbabwean, speaks directly to the reader telling not only her story of growing up female in a patriarchal society, but also those of the women around her. <br /><br />In the opening sentence, Tambu makes no apologies regarding her lack of emotion toward her brother's death. Because with no other male children in the family, she is now the one afforded the opportunity of an education, a way to get off the homestead -- an escape.<br /><br />But with that opportunity comes conflict -- a divide in family, the community, and even within Tambu herself. There is a constant struggle of loyalty. Trying to maintain balance between the traditions of her own culture while also adjusting to those of the Anglicized missionary school. How to better her station in life without coming across as "better than." This line is one that all of the female characters -- mother, sisters, cousin, aunts -- come to face. A choosing between self and surrender.<br /><br />The book had a warm conversational tone and was sprinkled with words in Shona, the native language, to describe everyday household items, endearments, greetings and ceremonies in a way that helped to fully immerse the reader in the story. <br /><br />My only fault with the book would be the abrupt ending. It felt as if it were being set up for the release of another book or second half. It somewhat jolted me out of the experience and put me back into role of consumer. It wasn't necessary, I already cared about Tambu at that point and would have sought out the rest of her story without the nudge. <br /><br /><br /><br /> <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /> <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /> <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="384721922019066626" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


