    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1464244458" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1464244458" />
    <a title="Lorraine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12034546-lorraine"><img alt="Lorraine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609874355p2/12034546.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1464244458?book_show_action=true">Dec 09, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lorraine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lorraine" href="/user/show/12034546-lorraine">Lorraine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1464244458" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17262942014646090158">I battled with this book. Until about 80% into it, I was not clear about its direction and had to re-read the reviews which hailed it as a literary germ.<br/><br/>Tsitsi is an excellent writer but I found her diction a bit elitist. I don&apos;t mind using the dictionary every now and then then the book becomes a bit of hard work. Unless you are reading for academic prowess, books should be a sort of escapism from the everyday stresses.<br/><br/>The storyline was very interesting and captivating. It is not everyday one r</span>
  <span id="freeText17262942014646090158" style="display:none">I battled with this book. Until about 80% into it, I was not clear about its direction and had to re-read the reviews which hailed it as a literary germ.<br /><br />Tsitsi is an excellent writer but I found her diction a bit elitist. I don't mind using the dictionary every now and then then the book becomes a bit of hard work. Unless you are reading for academic prowess, books should be a sort of escapism from the everyday stresses.<br /><br />The storyline was very interesting and captivating. It is not everyday one reads about patriarch, colonialism, cultural prejudice and its effect on African women and girls. The construction of the plot was long- winded rendering the storyline laborious.<br /><br />in terms of construction, the setting of the plot takes about 200 pages of the book (80%), the climax is when Nyasha has a psychological breakdown (3 pages) and then the story abruptly reaches its climax and ends. I'd have liked to see how Tambu then continues with her metamorphosis at Sacred Heart in light of what had transpired.<br /><br />The 3 women were such a contrast. Lucia, uneducated, unmarried therefore given a lower status within the family, commands respect because she stands up for herself. Tambu's mother, timidly moving about the homestead and readily accepts the status quo. Maiguru, educated and contributed to the family's financial prosperity is reduced to a second class citizen in her home.<br /><br />Nyash and Tambu. Worlds apart. Nyasha wanted for nothing but always yearning for more. More what? Tambu came fromhumble beginnings and never forgot it.<br /><br />if there's a sequel, I can't wait to get my hands on it. 4 full stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17262942014646090158" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


